AWS Organizations, and service control policies.

Most real companies don't have just one AWS account. They have dozens, or hundreds, split by environment, by team, by blast radius, and by billing line. AWS Organizations turns that fleet into one managed tree. There's a root at the top, nestable organizational units, or O-Us, as containers, and accounts as the leaves. Two account types matter. The management account owns the org, pays all the bills, and is the only one that can attach service control policies or create new member accounts, so you don't run workloads there. Every other account is a member.

You reach for Organizations for four things. Consolidated billing: one invoice, with volume discounts and savings plans applying across the whole fleet. Programmatic account creation: spinning up new accounts as code, which is the basis of landing zones. Centralized governance: rules enforced from above. And cross-account sharing: sharing reserved instances, savings plans, and A-M-Is through Resource Access Manager.

The governance lever is the service control policy, or S-C-P. Attached to the root, an O-U, or an account, it defines the maximum permissions for every principal in scope, including the root user of member accounts. Two things to keep straight. An S-C-P does not grant anything; it only caps, and I-A-M must still grant the action. And it does not apply to the management account, or to service-linked roles. Most orgs run a deny-list: start from full-A-W-S-access, then add explicit denies. Two patterns are worth recognizing. A region restriction denies any action whose requested region isn't on your approved list, using not-action to exempt global services so they don't break. And an org lock-in denies the leave-organization action, so member accounts can't escape governance.
